qas.question: What action results in something being "Sent Up For Good?"

answers.text: If any boy produces an outstanding piece of work

qas.question: What does a student receive when work is Sent Up For Good?
When a student has work Sent Up For Good, who signs the card that they receive?

answers.text: House Master, tutor and division master

qas.question: Where is work that has been Sent Up For Good stored?
How many pieces of work are Sent Up For Good each decade on average?
How many Head of Department are there at Eton?
What process at Eton is as clear as day to most Eton boys?
Who takes the Sending Up For Good piece of work to the College Archives?

context: <a0_0>If any boy produces an outstanding piece of work<a0_0/>, it may be "<b6_0>Sent Up For Good<b6_0/>", storing the effort in the <a3_0>College Archives<a3_0/> for posterity. This award has been around since the <b4_0><b5_0>18<b5_0/><b4_0/>th century. As Sending Up For Good is fairly infrequent, the process is rather mysterious to many of Eton's boys. First, the master wishing to Send Up For Good must gain the permission of the relevant Head of Department. Upon receiving his or her approval, the piece of work will be marked with Sent Up For Good and the student will receive <a1_0>a card<a1_0/> to be signed by <a2_0><b7_0>House Master<b7_0/>, tutor and division master<a2_0/>.
